\subsection{Conclusions}
The results of the \ac{MLEM} reconstruction are heavily affected by noise in measurements.
First of all, the \ac{UAV}s were localized using \ac{GPS} method that might be effect by a position error of several meters.
The position error propagates to the uncertainty of the Compton cone origins.
Furthermore, the real \ac{pix} sensors produced many outliers --- Compton cones pointing upwards or not intersecting any source position. 
The noisy measurements are caused by the working principle of unshielded single-layer Compton camera, where ionizing particles coming from different directions might affect the Cone reconstruction procedure.
However, the comparison of \ac{MLEM} estimate (figure \ref{e1:lam}) and back-projection (figure \ref{e1:bp}) shows that the \ac{MLEM} significantly improved the reconstruction quality.
The $\SI{1900}{\mega\becquerel}$ source was localized (despite the low number of recorded photons originating there) 
thanks to the weighting of the estimate  with sensitivity of detection in the \ac{MLEM} algorithm.
Better results might be achieved by using an active search strategy, where the drones are controlled on order to improve quality of the current \ac{MLEM} estimate, which is not the case in this scenario with pre-recorded measurements.

\section{Evaluation of MLEM and search strategy in simulation\label{chap:exp2}}
The \ac{MLEM} estimation method have been tested together with proposed search strategy in \textit{Gazebo} simulation. 

\subsection{Experiment setup}
The distribution and activity of the radioactive sources as well as the size of the area was identical as in the previous chapter.
Three drones flying $\SI{3}{\meter}$ above the ground were used during the experiment.  
Two drones were designated to the exploitation (visiting the positions where the sources of radiation are present based on the latest \ac{MLEM} estimate), one to exploration (visiting positions with the lowest sensitivity). 
The initial trajectories (covering the whole space uniformly) were computed using the MRS UAV system.
After the \ac{UAV}s finished the trajectories, the proposed search strategy was applied.

\subsection{Results}
The results of the \ac{MLEM} reconstruction are presented in figure \ref{fig:e2}.


