\section{Real-world experiment with simulated radiation\label{chap:exp3}}
The proposed search strategy has been tested using real \ac{UAV}s during the fiend experiments.
Since the real sources of radiation were not available, the ionizing radiation was simulated onboard each \ac{UAV}.
The main purpose of the experiment was to test the search strategy with real hardware and gain some experience with real-world conditions, where many things are not as simple as in simulation.

\subsection{Experiment setup}
The area of interest had size $100 \times 100\ \si{\meter}$, the resolution of each map cell was set to $\SI{0.5}{\meter}$.
The \ac{UAV}s were localized using \ac{GPS}.
The simulator of ionizing radiation was running onboard each \ac{UAV}, simulating the radiation coming from sources at predefined positions.
The communication between the base station (notebook with \textit{Intel i5-1240P} processor, $\SI{16}{\giga\byte}$ RAM, $\SI{4}{\giga\byte}$ GB GPU) and the \ac{UAv}s was established via \ac{wifi} network. 
In the initial phase, the drones were following the predefined trajectory (covering the area uniformly) to acquire first measurements.
Then the proposed search strategy took control - two drones were designated to the exploitation, one to exploration.

\subsection{Results}
The results of the real-world flight with simulated radiation data are presented in figure \ref{fig:e3}.
The estimate of radioactivity distribution 

